<DOC><DOCNO> AP880713-0002 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2330EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Helicopter 1stLd-Writethru a0742 07-13 0247</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Helicopter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0250</SECOND><HEAD>Helicopter With Engine Afire Ditches In North Sea; All 21 AboardRescued</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: New throughout with helicopter forced down by engine fire;details. No pickup.</NOTE><DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A helicopter carrying oil workers froman offshore platform ditched in the North Sea in rough weatherWednesday after an engine caught fire, but all 21 aboard wererescued, the coast guard said.   No injuries were reported among the two crewmembers and 19passengers who were on their way to Sumburgh in the remote ShetlandIslands, 150 miles north of the Scottish mainland, the coast guardsaid.   After taking off from Shell Oil's Safe Felicia accomodationplatform near the North Cormorant oil rig, 75 miles northeast ofSumburgh, the pilot of the S61 Sikorsky helicopter discovered oneengine afire, officials said.   The pilot radioed for help and made a controlled descent ontothe ocean surface 17 miles east of Lerwick in the Shetlands,despite rain, rough water, and heavy winds.   The helicopter stayed afloat long enough for the passengers todon survival suits and get into life rafts. Within 30 minutes theywere picked up by rescue helicopters and a lifeboat, said BobMcQueen, general manager of British International Helicopters inAberdeen.   Among the rescuers were men who took part in the rescue missionafter last week's Piper Alpha explosion and fire in the North Sea _the world's worst oil rig disaster, in which 166 men were killed.Sixty-four were saved.</TEXT></DOC>